did.abstract: This collection includes 3,538 glass plate negatives created by photographer Edmund L. Wolven. Most of the images are of Vassar College people, events, buildings and grounds, but there is a subset that relates to Poughkeepsie and other local educational institutions.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Edmund L. Wolven, born in Poughkeepsie in 1876, worked for many schools and colleges in the area. He began taking photographs for Vassar College in the late 1890s, and became the official college photographer between approximately 1900 and 1910.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: This collection includes 3,538 glass plate negatives created by photographer Edmund Wolven. Most of the images are of Vassar College people, events, buildings and grounds, but there is a subset that relates to other local educational institutions and Poughkeepsie.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is organized into thirteen series: Series I. Athletics, 1902-1940; Series II. Buildings and Grounds, 1897-1940; Series III. Class Portraits, 1901-1943; Series IV. Commencement and Reunion, 1900-1942; Series V. Drama, Music, and Dance, 1900-1936; Series VI. Events and Festivals, 1915-1944; Series VII. Founder's Day, 1900-1935; Series VIII. Miscellaneous Vassar College Subjects, 1900-1940; Series IX. Non-Vassar, 1900-1929; Series X. Portraits of Individuals, circa 1910s - circa 1940; Series XI. Professor Fite's Reproductions, 1925; Series XII. Student Organizations, 1915-1936; and Series XIII. Vassar Paintings and Historical Images, 1900-1940.

accessrestrict.head: Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research according to the regulations of the Vassar College Archives and Special Collections Library without any additional restrictions.

altformavail.head: Other Formats
altformavail.p: The E. L. Wolven Glass Plate Negative Collection has been digitized and is available to view online in the Vassar College Digital Library. Each negative has a corresponding identification number, which can be seen in square brackets next to the negative's physical box number on the container list below. Inputing this identification number in the Digital Library search bar will result in the corresponding negative.

did.unittitle: Series I. Athletics,

scopecontent.p: This series consists of photographs of athletics activities and events at Vassar College, including almost yearly images of Field Day from 1916-1936; team portraits and action photographs from field hockey, basketball, baseball, tennis, fencing, lacrosse, and archery events. There are also images from horse shows, golfing, swimming, and winter sports. Topics documented in this series include the evolution of women's uniforms, as well as developments in athletic fields and equipment.

arrangement.p: Organized into subseries by subject and sub-arranged chronologically.

did.unittitle: Series II. Buildings and Grounds,

scopecontent.p: This series consists of images of Vassar College buildings (interior and exterior) and the landscapes of the campus and surrounding area. Highlights include views of Vassar Lake before the Raymond Avenue elevation change in 1966, the southeast portion of campus before Sunset Lake was created, Raymond Avenue before the Faculty Row houses were built, the living and research spaces in the Maria Mitchell Observatory, and maintenance staff harvesting ice with saws and horse-drawn ice plows.

arrangement.p: Organized into subseries by subject and sub-arranged chronologically.

did.unittitle: Series III. Class Portraits,

scopecontent.p: This series contains freshman and senior class portraits from a selection of graduating classes between 1901 and 1943. The images were taken using extra large plates (14 x 17 inches) which provides access to fine details and allows for easier identification of individuals.

did.unittitle: Series IV. Commencement and Reunion,

bioghist.p: In the first half of the 20th century, Vassar's commencement and reunion were part of a 4-5 day long celebration that included a variety of events and traditions. Steady events included Baccalaureate Sunday, the alumnae parade, Class Day exercises, and commencement. Other activities changed over the decades, and included concerts and lectures, luncheons and suppers, tree ceremonies, May Pole dances, and for many years the III Hall Play was repeated for families and alumnae.

scopecontent.p: This series consists primarily of images from commencement, Class Day exercises, and the alumnae parade. Photos of Sophomores picking daisies for the Daisy Chain are also included. Early graduates and significant alumnae such as Harriette Warner Bishop and Helen D. Woodward (both VC 1867), Mary Augusta Jordan (VC 1876), Harriot Stanton Blatch (VC 1878), Julia Lathrop (VC 1880), and Blanche Ferry Hooker (VC 1894) are pictured; as are faculty, administrators and trustees such as C. Mildred Thompson, Ella McCaleb, Herbert E. Mills, and the astronomers Caroline Furness and Mary Whitney.

arrangement.p: Organized into subseries by subject and sub-arranged chronologically.

did.unittitle: Series V. Drama, Music, and Dance,

scopecontent.p: This series consists of images of plays, skit shows, dance performances, and musical events. It comprises the largest series in the Wolven collection. Junior and sophomore parties were generally skit shows written by students. These events included racist and stereotypical costumes and performances, including use of blackface. The major dramatic productions ("Hall" plays) include previously produced pieces, as well as material written by students, faculty, and alumnae, including Edna St. Vincent Millay.

did.unittitle: Series VI. Events and Festivals,

scopecontent.p: This series includes images of events that were not as large or well-photographed as Field Day, Founder's Day, and commencement and reunion activities. The annual class tree ceremonies, proms, 50th college anniversary, maypole dances, conferences, protests, community work, and other activities are included. Highlights include pageants and performances from the College's 50th Anniversary celebrations, the 1924 Institute for a Christian Basis of World Relations, and 1920's Township Day, which welcomed Arlington children to campus to participate in athletics and dramatic performances.

arrangement.p: Organized into subseries by subject and sub-arranged chronologically.

did.unittitle: Series VII. Founder's Day,

scopecontent.p: This series consists of images of Founder's Day, an annual Vassar College tradition that has included a variety of activities since the first celebration on April 29th, 1866--Matthew Vassar's birthday. The images in this series document visits to the founder's grave, step-singing and the Song Contest, the faculty-student baseball game, parades, and various performances. Attendees of the baseball game, the parades, and the performances were encouraged to dress in costume, according to either a predetermined theme or individual whim. With some frequency, these costumes and performances were based on racist or stereotypical representations of marginalized groups, including blackface, redface, and yellowface. Similarly, the faculty play or skit show which was given on the evening of Founder's Day, included racist and stereotypical costumes and performances.

arrangement.p: Organized into subseries by year or year group, and sub-arranged alphabetically by title.

did.unittitle: Series VIII. Miscellaneous Vassar College Subjects,

scopecontent.p: This series consists of additional subjects related to Vassar College that do not fall under any previous series. Selected highlights from this set include group portraits of the Good Fellowship Club men's and women's basketball teams, a classroom scene of a "preparedness course" on shorthand taught shortly after the U.S. entered World War I, and students working at Lincoln Center, the Poughkeepsie organization that assisted the poor.

did.unittitle: Series IX. Non-Vassar,

scopecontent.p: This series includes Wolven's portraits of classes at St. Stephen's College (now Bard College), the Putnam School, and Riverview Military Academy, as well as views of Poughkeepsie streets and landscapes, including the Mid-Hudson Bridge while it was under construction.

did.unittitle: Series X. Portraits of Individuals,

scopecontent.p: This series consists of portraits of individuals, including Vassar College students and faculty. Most individuals pictured are unidentified.

arrangement.p: Arranged alphabetically by name or subject.

did.unittitle: Series XI. Professor Fite's Reproductions,

scopecontent.p: This series consists of photographs of reproductions of historical documents for political science and history professor Emerson David Fite.

did.unittitle: Series XII. Student Organizations,

scopecontent.p: This series consists of group portraits of student organizations taken for the Vassar College yearbook and to be sold as souvenirs. Portraits of the athletic teams are included in Series I. Athletics. The groups in this series include the Vassar College Choir, the Glee Club, the Mandolin Club, class officers, and the staff of various student publications.

arrangement.p: Organized into subseries alphabetically by subject, and sub-arranged chronologically.

did.unittitle: Series XIII. Vassar Paintings and Historical Images,

scopecontent.p: This series consists of photographs of portraits of Matthew Vassar, his family, and other individuals related to the college's early history.
